quizzes.textContent:
[h1]CSS3 Transforms[/h1]

CSS3 transforms allow you to translate, rotate, scale, and skew elements.
A transformation is an effect that lets an element change shape, size, and position.
CSS3 supports 2D and 3D transformations. Let's take a look at the rotate transformation: [code format="css" codeId="622"]div {
   width: 200px;
   height: 100px;
   margin-top: 30px;
   background-color: #32CD32;
}[/code]
The div element before the transform will look like this: [img id="2707" width="100%"]
Now let's apply the div element to rotate by [b]10deg[/b]:[code format="css" codeId="623"]div {
   width: 200px;
   height: 100px;
   margin-top: 30px;
   background-color: #32CD32;
   [b]transform: rotate(10deg);[/b]
}[/code]
And here is the result: [img id="2708" width="100%"]
The rotate() method rotates an element clockwise or counter-clockwise, according to a given degree.
[note][b]Negative value[/b] will result in a counter clockwise rotation. [/note]

quizzes.question:
Add the transformation property to rotate the element 45 degrees, counter-clockwise.
[!raw!]
transform: {0}({1}45deg);

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Using Negative Values[/h1]

As previously mentioned, using a positive value will rotate an element [b]clockwise[/b], and using a negative value will rotate the element [b]counter-clockwise[/b]. [code format="css" codeId="624"]div.positive {
   width: 200px;
   height: 100px;
   margin-top: 30px;
   background-color: #32CD32;
   transform: [b]rotate(10deg);[/b]
}
div.negative {
   width: 200px;
   height: 100px;
   margin-top: 30px;
   background-color: #32CD32;
   transform: [b]rotate(-10deg);[/b]
}[/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2709" width="100%"]
